{
  "texts": [
    "Coresets let us learn a model over a much smaller set of points, while still yielding a model that is within a factor of 1 + of the optimal loss on the original training set.",
    "There- fore, a coreset represents a sufficient set of points for a given task, while most influence estimation methods identify the most necessary points -the points without which performance would decline, even given many other points from the original dataset.",
    "Another difference is that coresets are often motivated by efficiency concerns, whereas influence estimation is more motivated by the need to understand the data and its impact on a model-specifically, a model trained on the entire training data.",
    "Coreset construction often involves submodular optimization (Bilmes, 2022), so that an efficient, greedy approach finds a nearly-optimal set of points.",
    "However, this also means that if there are multiple, equally-important points, submodular optimization will select one and skip the others as redundant."
  ]
}